      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Labor activism in the U.S. was primarily focused on securing fundamental rights for workers, such as the right to organize, collect better wages, and mitigate dangerous working conditions, rather than seizing political power. Movements like the formation of the United Mine Workers often involved violent confrontations from corporate interests and security forces, underscoring the genuine struggle for basic protections. While unions did influence economic policies, their historical goal was to restore bargaining power to a class of workers with little leverage in individual contracts. This dynamic often brought them into conflict with the business elite of the Gilded Age and early Progressive Era.",
      "source": "target",
